If you want to take a realistic example, look at 2 different sports' teams.  The players on each side play the same game, and it's not because they don't live in the same hometown that grounds for communication between should be forbidden.  <br>
<br>
And returning to the actual theme of discussions, lemme refer you a couple more analogies:<br>
When in school, is that all you have to talk about?<br>
When in a bar, do you always have to talk about booze?<br>
When in a casino, do you always have to discuss money?<br>
<br>
Plus, you have to admit the game itself is getting rather repetitive, and no matter what encounter is involved in a given dispute, you've probably heard about it before, with different people, guilds, and maybe slightly different circumstances.  I'm sick to my throat of hearing about Ragefire nowadays, and I've wasted 2 weeks of my life on that bugger myself, but it's always the same old shit, some cleric camping him for days on end only to be steamrolled at the last minute.  <br>
<br>
Real life however is much more dynamic than EQ, and  maybe if you crawled out of your cocoon, you'd see why.  Why do you find Real Life topics so vexing anyways?  Seems to me there's an underlying issue you need to resolve... <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=111343">Nektar Nefaste</a><br>
Shaman of 60 Farts


